  "topic": "File Permissions and Ownership",
  "slides": [
    {
      "slideId": 1,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "What Are File Permissions in Linux?"
        },
        {
          "type": "definition",
          "value": "File permissions control who can read, modify, or execute a file in Linux. They protect the system from unwanted changes."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Every file has an owner, a group, and permissions that decide what actions are allowed. Permissions prevent accidental or unauthorized access."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Access", "Meaning"],
            ["r (read)", "View or read the file content"],
            ["w (write)", "Modify or delete the file"],
            ["x (execute)", "Run the file as a program/script"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "If you're not sure about a file permission, check it with ls -l before changing anything."
        }
      ],
      "video": {
        "platform": "youtube",
        "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LnKoncbQBsM"
      }
    },


    {
      "slideId": 2,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Using chmod to Change Permissions"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "chmod changes permission rules. You can use letters (r,w,x) or numbers (chmod 755 file)."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "ls -l file.txt",
          "description": "Check file permissions before modifying."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "chmod 755 script.sh",
          "description": "Owner: read/write/execute | Group & Others: read/execute (common for scripts)."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "chmod u+rwx file.txt",
          "description": "Give the owner full permissions."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Numeric", "Meaning"],
            ["7 = rwx", "Full access"],
            ["6 = rw-", "Read & write"],
            ["5 = r-x", "Read & execute"],
            ["4 = r--", "Read only"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "image",
          "url": "https://cdn.hashnode.com/res/hashnode/image/upload/v1682516642007/1faffae6-8424-453b-a824-8f8348a727d4.png?auto=compress,format&format=webp",
          "alt": "Example: One can check and understand these permissions by ls -ltr command and get a better understanding of the permissions of files and directories in their system"
        },
        {
          "type": "image",
          "url": "https://github.coventry.ac.uk/pages/CUEH/245CT/4_Privesc/images/perms1.png",
          "alt": "Explaination of this output."
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "chmod 755 is one of the safest defaults for executable scripts."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },
    {
      "slideId": 3,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Using chown to Change Ownership"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "chown changes who owns the file. Normally only the root or original owner can transfer ownership."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "chown user file.txt",
          "description": "Make a specific user the new owner."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "chown user:group file.txt",
          "description": "Change both owner and group at the same time."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Command", "Purpose"],
            ["chown user file", "Give file to a new user"],
            ["chown user:group file", "Change both file owner & group"],
            ["sudo chown ...", "Required when changing ownership outside your user"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Always double-check owner and group after changes using ls -l."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },
        {
      "slideId": 4,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Quick Knowledge Check"
        },
        {
          "type": "quiz",
          "question": "Which command gives ownership of file.txt to a user named alex?",
          "options": [
            "A: chmod alex file.txt",
            "B: chown alex file.txt",
            "C: chown file.txt alex",
            "D: chmod 777 file.txt"
          ],
          "correctAnswer": 1
        },
        {
          "type": "quiz",
          "question": "Which permission number means 'read & write only'?",
          "options": [
            "A: 7 (rwx)",
            "B: 6 (rw-)",
            "C: 5 (r-x)",
            "D: 4 (r--)"
          ],
          "correctAnswer": 1
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Remember: chmod changes permissions, chown changes ownership."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    }
  ]
